### 1. Prototype Kya Hai?

- Har object ka ek internal hidden link hota hai → `[[Prototype]]`
- Yeh link dusre object ko point karta hai
- Us dusre object se properties aur methods **inherit** hote hain

**Access karne ke tarike:**

```js
const obj = {};

Object.getPrototypeOf(obj);     // Recommended way
obj.__proto__;                  // Old way (production mein avoid karo)
```

### 2. Prototype Chain (Sabse Important Concept)

Jab aap koi property ya method access karte ho:

1. Pehle object khud mein dekho
2. Agar nahi mila → uske `[[Prototype]]` mein dekho
3. Agar wahan bhi nahi → uske prototype ke prototype mein dekho...
4. Chain `Object.prototype` pe khatam hoti hai
5. Uske baad `null` milta hai

**Example Chain:**
```
[] (Array instance)
   ↓
Array.prototype
   ↓
Object.prototype
   ↓
null
```

### 3. Constructor Function + Prototype

```js
function Hero(name) {
  this.name = name;           // Own property
}

// Method prototype pe add karo (memory efficient)
Hero.prototype.greet = function() {
  return `Hello, I am ${this.name}`;
};

const hero1 = new Hero("Thor");
const hero2 = new Hero("Loki");

hero1.greet();   // "Hello, I am Thor"
```

**Note:** `greet` method dono objects pe alag-alag nahi bana – yeh shared hai `Hero.prototype` pe.

### 4. Inheritance (Prototype Linking)

```js
function Warrior(name, weapon) {
  Hero.call(this, name);      // Parent constructor call
  this.weapon = weapon;
}

// Link prototypes (Inheritance)
Object.setPrototypeOf(Warrior.prototype, Hero.prototype);

Warrior.prototype.attack = function() {
  return `${this.name} attacks with ${this.weapon}!`;
};

const warrior = new Warrior("Bjorn", "Axe");

warrior.greet();   // Inherited from Hero
warrior.attack();  // Own method
```

### 5. Key Methods & Properties

| Method / Property               | Kya Karta Hai? |
|---------------------------------|----------------|
| `Object.getPrototypeOf(obj)`    | Object ka prototype return karta hai |
| `Object.setPrototypeOf(obj, proto)` | Prototype set karta hai |
| `obj.hasOwnProperty('key')`     | Sirf own property check karta hai (inherited nahi) |
| `obj.isPrototypeOf(other)`      | Check karta hai kya yeh prototype chain mein hai |
| `obj instanceof Constructor`    | Check karta hai constructor ka prototype chain mein hai |

### 6. `__proto__` vs `prototype`

| Property              | Belongs To          | Meaning |
|-----------------------|---------------------|--------|
| `obj.__proto__`       | Instance (object)   | Us object ka `[[Prototype]]` link |
| `Constructor.prototype` | Constructor function | Naye objects ke liye blueprint (jo unka `[[Prototype]]` banega) |

### 7. Modern Way – ES6 `class` (Syntactic Sugar)

```js
class Hero {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  greet() {
    return `Hello, I am ${this.name}`;
  }
}

class Warrior extends Hero {
  constructor(name, weapon) {
    super(name);
    this.weapon = weapon;
  }

  attack() {
    return `${this.name} attacks with ${this.weapon}!`;
  }
}
```

**Under the hood** class bhi prototype chaining hi use karti hai.

### Best Practices & Gotchas

- Methods hamesha `prototype` pe add karo (memory saving)
- `__proto__` production code mein mat use karo
- `Object.setPrototypeOf()` ya `class` + `extends` use karo
- `hasOwnProperty()` use karo jab inherited properties ko ignore karna ho
- Prototype chain lambi mat banao (performance issue ho sakta hai)

**Key Takeaway:**  
JavaScript mein inheritance **delegation** ke through hota hai — objects dusre objects se properties/methods maangte hain via prototype chain.
